		<h3>Gaming with Biofeedback</h3>
		<p><img src="images/ok.jpg" width="400" style="float:right; margin: 10px 0px 2px 8px;-webkit-box-shadow: 4px 4px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25); -moz-box-shadow: 4px 4px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);" />
The end goal is for Gaming with Biofeedback is to create two (or more) short games that are designed to affect the autonomic nervous system (this is in charge of several functions including:  heart rate, respiration rate, salivation, perspiration, and pupil response). Students will work to design the game and then find the appropriate sensors for the installation (dumpster diving permitted!). One idea is to have the users become more participatory in the game-play. With practice (and how much practice is a good question) can they begin to control their heartrate, etc.  as they play an action-packed game? Unlike traditional experiments, all data is shown to the players in real time so they are meshed in the experience and in the learning process. Led by Mina Johnson-Glenberg.<br/>
<br/>
		</p>
		
